 a longer tradition of the New York metropolitan sound, dating back to the early 1900s, cultural historian Jim Cullen explores how each man drew from the city’s diverse racial and ethnic influences. His study explains how, despite frequently releasing songs that questioned the American dream, Springsteen and Joel were able to appeal to wide audiences during both the national uncertainty of the 1970s and the triumphalism of the Reagan era. By placing these two New York–area icons in a new context, Bridge and Tunnel Boys allows us to hear their most beloved songs with new appreciation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPopular musiczUnited Statesy1971-1980xHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musiczUnited Statesy1981-1990xHistory and criticism. 0aRock musiczUnited Statesy1971-1980xHistory and criticism. 0aRock musiczUnited Statesy1981-1990xHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aBruce Springsteen, Billy Joel, Long Island, Asbury Park, New Jersey, New York, music, metropolitan, rock, 1970s, history, art history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023z978311131812708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079131040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197883524540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978835245423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978835245/original  a978-3-11-079131-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2